        <name>13.3.3.4 Finding areas</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Calculate the area enclosed by the curve \(y=x^3\) and the line \(y=x\). [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;The curve \(y=x^3\) and the line \(y=x\) intersect at \(x=-1,0,1\). Between 0 and 1 the graph is above the \(x\) axis and \(y=x\) is greater than \(y=x^3\). Between -1 and 0, the graph is below the \(x\) axis and \(y=x^3\) is greater than \(y=x\). Hence
    the area is \[- \int_{-1}^0 (x^3 -x) \,\mathrm{d}x + \int_0^1 (x-x^3) \, \mathrm{d}x = {@ta4@}\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A sketch of the graph is shown below.&lt;/p&gt;
